        <example>
            <title>2</title>
            <p>A certain prescription medicine is supposed to contain an average of 250 parts per
                million (ppm) of a certain chemical. If the concentration is higher than this, the
                drug may cause harmful side effects; if it is lower, the drug may be ineffective.
                The manufacturer runs a check to see if the mean concentration in a large shipment
                conforms to the target level of 250 ppm or not. A simple random sample of 100
                portions is tested, and the sample mean concentration is found to be 247 ppm with a
                sample standard deviation of 12 ppm. Again, here is a figure that represents this
                example where the changes are marked in blue:</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image373.gif" alt="A large circle represents
the population, which is the shipment. &mu; represents the concentration of the chemical. We need to
answer &quot;is the mean concentration the required 250ppm or not?&quot; Selected from the population is a 
sample of size n=100, represented by a smaller circle. x-bar for this sample is 247 and S=12."/>
            <p>The changes are similar to example 1: we no longer assume that the population
                standard deviation is known, and instead
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091027-0500"?>use
                <?oxy_insert_end?>the sample standard deviation
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091032-0500"?>of<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091032-0500" content="is"?>
                12. Again, the problem was thus changed from a z-test problem to a t-test
                problem.</p>
            <p>However, as we mentioned earlier, due to the large sample size (n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091044-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091044-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>100) there should not be much difference whether we use the z-test
                or the t-test. The sample standard deviation,
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091052-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091052-0500" content="S"?>,
                is expected to be close enough to the population standard deviation <m:math
                    overflow="scroll">
                    <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                </m:math> . We'll see this as we solve the problem.</p>
        </example>
        <p>Let's carry out the t-test for both
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091107-0500"?>of
            <?oxy_insert_end?>these problems:</p>
        <p>
            <em>Example 1:</em>
        </p>
        <p>1. <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091126-0500"?>There are
            <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091129-0500" content="N"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091130-0500"?>n<?oxy_insert_end?>o
            change<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091132-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>
            in the hypotheses being tested:</p>
        <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image374.gif" alt="H_0: &mu; = 500,    H_a: &mu;
&gt; 500"/>
        <p>2. The conditions that allow us to use the t-test are met since:</p>
        <p> (i)
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091141-0500"?>T<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091141-0500" content="t"?>he
            sample is
            random<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091144-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
        <p> (ii) SAT-M is known to vary normally in the population (which is crucial
            here<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091154-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            since the sample size is only 4).</p>
        <p> In other words, we are in the following situation:</p>
        <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image328.gif" alt="A table which has two columns and two rows,
and is titled &quot;Conditions: z-test for a population mean.&quot; The column headings are: &quot;Small
Sample Size&quot; and &quot;Large Sample Size. &quot; The row headings are &quot;Variable varies normally
in the population&quot; and &quot;Variable doesn't vary normally in the population.&quot; Here is the data
in the table by cell in &quot;Row, Column: Value&quot; format:
            Variable varies normally in the population, Small sample size: OK (this is the case this example falls in);
            Variable varies normally in the population, Large sample size: OK;
            Variable doesn't vary normally in the population, Small sample size: NOT OK;
            Variable doesn't vary normally in the population, Large sample size: OK;"/>
        <p> The test statistic is <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mi>t</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mover>
                                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                            </m:mover>
                            <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mfrac>
                            <m:mi>s</m:mi>
                            <m:msqrt>
                                <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            </m:msqrt>
                        </m:mfrac>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>550</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>500</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mfrac>
                            <m:mn>100</m:mn>
                            <m:msqrt>
                                <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                            </m:msqrt>
                        </m:mfrac>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>
        </p>
        <p> The data (represented by the sample mean) are 1 standard error above the null value.</p>
        <p>3. Finding the
            p-value<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091228-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
        <p> Recall that in general the p-value is calculated under the null distribution of the test
            statistic,
            <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091542-0500" comment="remove paragraph break"?>which<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091259-0500"?>,<?oxy_comment_end?><?oxy_insert_end?></p>
        <p> in the t-test
            case<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091546-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            is t(n-1). In our case<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091553-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091555-0500"?>in
            which<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091557-0500" content="where"?> n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091559-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091600-0500"?>
            <?oxy_insert_end?>4, the p-value is calculated under the t(3) distribution:</p>
        <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image376.gif" alt="A t(3) distribution with t-scores
0 and 1 marked. The p-value is the area under the curve to the right of t-score 1."/>
        <p>Using statistical software, we find that the p-value is 0.196. For comparison purposes,
            the p-value that we got when we carried out the z-test for this problem (when we assumed
            that 100 is the known <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
            </m:math> rather the calculated sample standard deviation<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091702-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091640-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091640-0500" content="S"?>)
            was 0.159.</p>
