        <p>It is not surprising that the p-value of the t-test is
            larger<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091739-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            since the t distribution has fatter tails. Even though in this particular case the
            difference between the two values does not have practical implications (since both are
            large and will lead to the same conclusion), the difference is
            no<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091759-0500"?>t
            <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091800-0500" content="n-"?>trivial.</p>
        <p>4. <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091813-0500"?>Making
            c<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091818-0500" content="C"?>onclusion<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091821-0500"?>s.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
        <p> The p-value (0.196) is large, indicating that the results are not significant. The data
            do not provide enough evidence to conclude that the mean SAT-M among Ross College
            students is higher than the national mean (500).</p>
        <p>Here is a
            <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091916-0500" comment="please use subscripts in graphic below for Ha and Ho"?>summary:<?oxy_comment_end?></p>
        <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image377.gif" alt="A large circle represents
all of the Students at Ross College. We are interested in finding &mu;, or the mean of the SAT-M
scores, which has a normal distribution. Our hypotheses are H_0: &mu; = 500 and H_a: &mu; &gt; 500.
We take a sample of size n = 4 from the population, represented by a smaller circle. For this sample,
we calculate that x-bar = 550 and S = 100. Our conditions are met, so we can find t = 1, and p-value
= .196 . This p-value is too high, so the conclusion is that H_0 cannot be rejected."/>
        <p>Example 2:</p>
        <p>1. <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091933-0500"?>There are
            <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091936-0500" content="N"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091936-0500"?>n<?oxy_insert_end?>o
            change<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091939-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>
            in <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091944-0500"?>the
            <?oxy_insert_end?>hypothes<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091947-0500"?>e<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091947-0500" content="i"?>s
            being
            tested<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T091952-0500"?>:<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
        <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image320.gif" alt="H_0: &mu; = 250, H_a: &mu; &ne; 250"/>
        <p>2. The conditions that allow us to use the t-test are met:</p>
        <p> (i) The sample is random</p>
        <p> (ii) The sample size is large enough for the Central Limit Theorem to apply and ensure<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T092003-0500" content="s"?>
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T092005-0500"?>the
            <?oxy_insert_end?>normality of <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mover>
                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                    </m:mover>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>. In other
            words<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T092010-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
            we are in the following situation:</p>
        <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image333.gif" alt="The same table as before. The case this
example is in is the &quot;Variable doesn't vary normally in the population, Large sample size&quot;
case. The table has two columns and two rows, and is titled &quot;Conditions: z-test for a population mean.&quot;
The column headings are: &quot;Small Sample Size&quot; and &quot;Large Sample Size. &quot; The row headings are
&quot;Variable varies normally in the population&quot; and &quot;Variable doesn't vary normally in the
population.&quot; Here is the data in the table by cell in &quot;Row, Column: Value&quot; format:
              Variable varies normally in the population, Small sample size: OK;
              Variable varies normally in the population, Large sample size: OK;
              Variable doesn't vary normally in the population, Small sample size: NOT OK;
              Variable doesn't vary normally in the population, Large sample size: OK (this is the case this example falls in);"/>
        <p> The test statistic is: <m:math overflow="scroll">
                <m:mrow>
                    <m:mi>t</m:mi>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mover>
                                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                            </m:mover>
                            <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mfrac>
                            <m:mi>s</m:mi>
                            <m:msqrt>
                                <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                            </m:msqrt>
                        </m:mfrac>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mfrac>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>247</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>25</m:mn>
                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                        <m:mfrac>
                            <m:mn>12</m:mn>
                            <m:msqrt>
                                <m:mn>100</m:mn>
                            </m:msqrt>
                        </m:mfrac>
                    </m:mfrac>
                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                    <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                    <m:mn>5</m:mn>
                </m:mrow>
            </m:math>
        </p>
        <p> The data (represented by the sample mean) are 2.5 standard errors below the null
            value.</p>
        <p>3. Finding the
            p-value<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T092031-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
        <!-\-<p> TUTOR WITHIN TEXT 2</p>-\->
        <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image379.gif" alt="A t(99) curve, for which the
horizontal axis has been labeled with t-scores of -2.5 and 2.5 . The area under the curve and to
the left of -2.5 and to the right of 2.5 is the p-value."/>
        <p>To find the p-value we use statistical software, and we calculate a p-value of 0.014 with
            a 95% confidence interval of (244.619, 249.381). For comparison purposes, the output we
            got when we carried out the z-test for the same problem was a p-value of 0.012 with a
            95% confidence interval of (244.648, 249.352).</p>
