    <section>
            <title>To Summarize</title>
            <body>
                <p>1. In hypothesis testing for the population mean
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102747-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?><m:math
                        overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math>
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102749-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>,
                    we distinguish between two cases:</p>
                <p> I. The less common case when
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102806-0500"?>the
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>population standard deviation
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102809-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?><m:math
                        overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102811-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    is known.</p>
                <p> II. The more practical case when the population standard deviation is unknown
                    and the sample standard deviation
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102836-0500"?>(s<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102839-0500" content="S"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102838-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    is used instead.</p>
                <p>2. In the case when <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> is
                    known<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102849-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    the test for <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> is called the z-test, and in case when <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> is unknown and s is used instead, the test is called the t-test.</p>
                <p>3. In both
                    cases<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102908-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    the null hypothesis is: <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                            <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p> and the alternative, depending on the context, is one of the following:</p>
                <p>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                <m:mi>a</m:mi>
                            </m:msub>
                            <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102937-0500"?>, or<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                <m:mi>a</m:mi>
                            </m:msub>
                            <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>&gt;</m:mo>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102943-0500"?>, or<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                <m:mi>a</m:mi>
                            </m:msub>
                            <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>≠</m:mo>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p>4. Both tests can be safely used as long as the following two conditions are
                    met:</p>
                <p> (i) The sample is random (or can at least be considered random in context).</p>
                <p> (ii) Either the sample size is large (n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102957-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>&gt;<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T102958-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>30) or, if not, the variable of interest can be assumed to
                    vary normally in the population.</p>
                <p>5. In the z-test, the test statistic is:</p>
                <p>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>z</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mfrac>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:mover>
                                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                                        <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                    </m:mover>
                                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                    <m:msub>
                                        <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                    </m:msub>
                                </m:mrow>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
                                    <m:msqrt>
                                        <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                    </m:msqrt>
                                </m:mfrac>
                            </m:mfrac>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p> whose null distribution is the standard normal
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103023-0500"?>distribution
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>(under which the p-values are calculated).</p>
                <p>6. In the t-test, the test statistic is:</p>
                <p>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi>t</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mfrac>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:mover>
                                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                                        <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                    </m:mover>
                                    <m:mo>−</m:mo>
                                    <m:msub>
                                        <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                    </m:msub>
                                </m:mrow>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mi>s</m:mi>
                                    <m:msqrt>
                                        <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                    </m:msqrt>
                                </m:mfrac>
                            </m:mfrac>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p> whose null distribution is
                    <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103038-0500" content="the"?> t(n<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103041-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>-<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103041-0500"?>
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>1) (under which the p-values are calculated).</p>
                <p>7. For large sample sizes, the z-test is a good approximation for the t-test.</p>
                <p>8. Confidence intervals can be used to carry out the two-sided test <image
                        style="block" src="../webcontent/image386.gif" alt="H_0: &mu; = &mu;_0 vs."/>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                <m:mi>a</m:mi>
                            </m:msub>
                            <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>≠</m:mo>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>, and in cases where
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103116-0500"?>H<sub>o</sub><?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103113-0500" content="Ho"?>
                    is rejected, the confidence interval can give insight into the value of the
                    population mean
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103122-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?><m:math
                        overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103123-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>.</p>
                <p>9. Here is a summary of
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103132-0500"?>which<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103134-0500" content="what"?>
                    test to use
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103141-0500"?>under which
                    conditions<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103148-0500" content="when"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101128T103149-0500"?>:<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
                <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image387.png" alt="A table. Here is the data
in the table:
With large sample size (regardless of whether the population is normal or not), we use the
z-test if sigma is known, otherwise we use the t-test, keeping in mind that the z-test is a good
approximation. With a small sample size, and normal population(* footnote), the z-test is used when
we know sigma, and when we don't, we use the t-test. With a small sample size which has a population shape
which is not normal or is unknown, we can't use the z-test or t-test. (*)Footnote: by &quot;Population
normal&quot; we mean that either the population is known to be normal, or else that the population can
be reasonably assumed to be normal as judged by the shape of the data histogram."/>
            </body>
        </section>
                        <p>The following activity will reinforce the topics illustrated in the
